Last week, I had a *miranda* moment about [allyship](http://www.guidetoallyship.com/) [@noauthor_guide_nodate] in our community.  

Allyship is not a badge to be discarded when inconvenient; it is about recognising that survivors have no such choice. The most important part of allyship, for me, is **trying to not be a reaver**, not how much time you devote to women's lib.

When we [harmfully communicate](http://www.shakesville.com/2011/12/harmful-communication-part-one-intent.html) [@mcewan_harmful_2011] to a survivor expressing triggered hurt that we do not accept their hurt because those who hurt them didn't *mean* it and are *nice people*, we are **reaving**. When we assume their hurt is irrational and trivialise, we are **reaving**. This is hard to accept, because, as always, "We meant it for the best". 

## miranda

In the 2005 space-western *Serenity* [@whedon_serenity_2005], a terrible secret, that the population of the planet Miranda had been eradicated by the inteplanetary Alliance, is hidden in the traumatised mind of a gifted young woman. 

```{r miranda, out.width = "85%", fig.align='center'}

knitr::include_graphics("../../figs/miranda.gif")

```

The crew of a small smuggling ship eventually uncover the secret. Overpowering the Alliance Operative, the captain broadwaves a signal about the genocide. 

> "I know the secret now. The truth that burned up River Tam's brain and set you after her. And the rest of the 'verse is gonna know it too. 'Cause they need too." - Captain Malcolm Reynolds

But it wasn't just genocide. 

## we meant it for the best

The G-23 Paxilon Hydrochlorate the Alliance added to the air processors to pacify the population caused almost all people to "just lay down" and die. However, there were exceptions.  

> I have to be quick! About a tenth of a percent of the population had the opposite reaction to the Pax. Their aggressor response increased beyond madness. They have become...

### reavers

<iframe width="400" height="300" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/U-NVs68X_S4" frameborder="0" allow="accelerometer; autoplay; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture" allowfullscreen></iframe>

No matter how much the Alliance "meant it for the best", it does not mitigate how horrific the outcome was. And what makes it most horrific is that the thirty million victims were afforded no agency; they never even knew. 


## demeaning everyday language

Everyday interactions are frequently dehumanising for me. Here's a really innocuous example; the kind I brush off all the time. Similar diplomacy is required when answering the question, *Where do you really come from?*

**Me**: Hi, I'm Charles. I am taking undergrad maths, supporting myself by teaching piano, and I'm thirty-* years old.

**Person**: Ah! So you're going to be a school teacher! 

They would argue there is no pejorative associated with school teaching. And there isn't. My husband is a gifted high school teacher and has a doctorate in literature; his work is important, challenging, and fulfilling. 

But. 

**Me** (to self): *Why is it **always** school teaching?*[^1][^2]

```{r fig.cap="Also me, to self."}

knitr::include_graphics("../../figs/code-like-a-girl.jpg")

```

[^1]: Sidenote, I was a [careers mathbassador](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=o0Rqz8Hgacc&feature=youtu.be&ab_channel=AMSITubn) (yeah, that's a link to my *movie*) for the Australian Mathematical Sciences Institute, and I'm here to tell you there are manifold opportunities for those in mathematical science. Opportunities in disciplines from ecology, psychology, to archaeology, in, you know,*any scientific discipline*. And that's in addition to industry opportunities in technology and finance. 
[^2]: Sadly, it should be noted, as a daughter and wife of school teachers, this profession is not valued in Australian society. Teachers are frequently pilloried in the press as greedy, when in fact they are monstrously over encumbered by ostensibly automated administration tasks.  

## perceived as inferior

Being a diminutive, brown, punk, middle-aged woman of little means with a foul mouth and too many opinions, I get to see a side of people they don't realise they are showing. 

Imagine the interaction above with a doctoral student in mathematics who is twenty-five and telling you about their professorial aspirations. Imagine you are at a conference and wish to make friends with similar research interests. Implied is that *they* are capable of this, but that I should limit myself. The why of which I am left to uncomfortably contemplate.

People often reveal *far* more than they realise through innocuous interactions with me. Language is laced with assumptions that I have limited capacity, that I will irrationally overreact; most importantly, that I am perceived by them as inferior by some, but usually many, measures. 

These are the knives I walk on. 

## a hill to die on

And sometimes these people are your friends. And sometimes, far more importantly, sometimes these are colleagues. It's easy to infer that because I find something they find easy hard, I will find all things hard. And it's an everlasting challenge to my patience and empathy to find ways to work productively with people who make that assumption.

To illustrate the case where it's genuinely worth addressing the problem, we consider an example from Melissa McEwan's excellent post on [Harmful Communication](http://www.shakesville.com/2011/12/harmful-communication-part-one-intent.html).

####  An example from Harmful Communication

 > Alex has a PhD in Subjectology. Jamie knows that Alex has a PhD in Subjectology, yet, during a discussion of Subject, Jamie, who has an interest in and is reasonably knowledgeable about Subject, condescendingly explains basics of Subject to Alex without regard for Alex's demonstrable proficiency. Alex expresses that Jamie's insistence on explaining basics makes Alex feel as though Jamie does not respect Alex's competency or intellectual capacity. Jamie, whose intent was actually to impress Alex, insists that hir intent was not to make Alex feel that way. Alex makes a valiant attempt to explain why Jamie behaving as though Alex doesn't know the basics of Alex's professional field is disrespectful, at which point Jamie gets miffed, reiterates that the intent was not to make Alex feel bad, accuses Alex of looking for things to get mad about, and misrepresents Alex's good faith attempt to address demeaning language as a personal attack on Jamie.
 
> Thus, what had started out as an inadvertent slight becomes a harmful exchange, as Jamie refuses to acknowledge that the effect of the action irrespective of its intent was hurtful to Alex, and deflects accountability by casting Alex as unreasonable. ([Harmful Communication](http://www.shakesville.com/2011/12/harmful-communication-part-one-intent.html))


## reaving

You will hurt and offend survivors, without knowing it. You will reave them. And no matter how hard you try, you will do it again. I think the least we all can do is *try* not to, and do our very best to be gracious when we inevitably reave. 

> If you decide to become an ally, but refuse to acknowledge that your words and actions are laced with oppression, you’re setting up yourself to fail. [Guide to Allyship](http://www.guidetoallyship.com/)

But to assume that intent innoculates the recipient of the offense from hurt is illogical. You apologise when you accidentally step on someone's foot, don't you?

> It is not merely unfair (although it is that, too) to deflect accountability by casting someone to whom you've done wrong as unreasonable, oversensitive, or alleging malice ("How could you think I intended to hurt you?!"), when they are being or doing no such thing. It is abusive.

> And it is abusive because it is emotionally manipulative.

> That's a difficult notion to accept for most of us, because most of us have engaged in this type of harmful communication at some point in our lives, even if it's not a regular habit. Even being presented with the idea that common defensiveness can be abusive is likely to elicit, in some readers, a magical intent response: I don't intend to abuse or manipulate people, so there's no way I'm doing it! ([Harmful Communication](http://www.shakesville.com/2011/12/harmful-communication-part-one-intent.html))

> But that's why this conversation is so important—because a lack of intent to harm doesn't guarantee that one will never harm.

And here's why it's *reaving* for survivors. Imagine now being someone who has been through countless interactions like the one above, but the offense under discussion was rape or physical violence. 

### another example

When I was fifteen, the state of Australia's welfare system was such that those who have lived through it are known as [Forgotten Australians](https://forgottenaustralians.org.au/). The safest place was the streets or couch surfing.

My friend's boyfriend invited me to stay with his uncle. We shared his uncle's bed, and he slept on the couch, which, was really generous of him. 

One night, we kissed. We shouldn't've. But we did. We betrayed my friend. We never kissed again, I felt terrible.

But from then on, in our shared bed, he would touch me at night. Paralysed, terrified I would be sleeping on the cold winter streets again, I lay very still, not reciprocating, hoping he would think I was asleep and stop. Eventually he would give up and go to sleep. 

Was he at fault? Or was he a teenage boy who was trying, ineptly, to seduce me? *It doesn't matter*. 

It doesn't change what it felt like for me. The powerlessness. The feeling the stakes are so high when it's so cold outside.  

There's no one to blame. There is no closure. 

Eventually I told my friend. I confessed to the kissing but said I didn't know how to get him to stop touching me. I tried to defend him.

She broke up with him. He stole what meagre possessions we had, CDs, etc., and sold them to people we thought we our best friends at school. Everyone turned on us, and we were still homeless. 


## we're all reavers

I don't understand everyone's lived experience. For example, as someone who has been treated with repugnance over my name, I cannot fathom how it would feel to have that repugnance transferred to my body.

<blockquote class="twitter-tweet"><p lang="en" dir="ltr">And now that I&#39;m flashing back to those people and the repugnance with which they treated me for changing my name, <a href="https://twitter.com/djnavarro?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw">\@djnavarro</a>. All I can think is how unimaginably awful it must be for you. 💜<br><br>Grrlfriend, you&#39;re a superhero. Please don&#39;t ever lose your strut. <a href="https://t.co/itdNIsDqpF">pic.twitter.com/itdNIsDqpF</a></p>&mdash; Charles T. Gray (\@cantabile) <a href="https://twitter.com/cantabile/status/1161887159843880961?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw">August 15, 2019</a></blockquote> <script async src="https://platform.twitter.com/widgets.js" charset="utf-8"></script>

I assume I've already unwittingly said something reavy to Dani, as we've exchanged many words. But what she has lived through means there will be wells and chasms of doubt and anxiety that are specific to her own experience, that I won't necessarily anticipate. The least I can do is try to anticipate and avoid them. Most importantly, I aspire to be gracious and empathetic when I do inevitably fuck up and reave. 

### the little mermaid

I live as Anderson's [*The Little Mermaid*](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Little_Mermaid). Not the Disney one with a happy ending. The original, where she trades her voice for legs and accepts that walking on her new feet will feel like walking on knives forever. That's what it's like to live with [trauma](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Complex_post-traumatic_stress_disorder).  

