)
</div>
</center>

When we're demeaned and triggered, we're stabbed in the gut, in *addition* to the knives we walk on daily. 

Real allyship is about recognising that survivors walk on knives **every day**, and doing what little you can not to make the pain worse. My childhood was sad; it's enough to say that, over twenty years ago, I felt it was time to make a *real* attempt and kicked the chair out from under me. But, as I hung there swinging, the rope tightening about my neck, I decided **I would live**, even if it meant walking on knives forever. 


### allyship

Allyship, for me, means accepting we can reave others, and *trying* and failing and *trying* again not to. Those who intentionally hurt are **not worth** expecting anything from, and not worth my energy, I simply remove myself at the first opportunity. If I am trying to communicate my hurt to you, it is a mark of respect, an implicit message to accompany the ever-present, but rarely acknowledged, explicit message that I understand you meant no harm but I am still hurt and confused. It is rarely taken as a sign of respect, despite my painstakingly patient efforts.

<blockquote class="twitter-tweet" data-conversation="none"><p lang="en" dir="ltr">There is nothing more excoriating than the &quot;ally&quot; who pressures you to debrief their quasi-acknowledged wrongdoing so that they can ostensibly learn, then doubles down on character assassinations. A shot at The Don&#39;ts (<a href="https://t.co/BcGKzXTS0I">https://t.co/BcGKzXTS0I</a>) bingo. <br><br>Then ghosts you. <a href="https://t.co/dypWkmM4lz">pic.twitter.com/dypWkmM4lz</a></p>&mdash; Charles T. Gray (\
@cantabile) <a href="https://twitter.com/cantabile/status/1160671444730179584?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw">August 11, 2019</a></blockquote> <script async src="https://platform.twitter.com/widgets.js" charset="utf-8"></script>

### CoCs are not preventing reaving

If we're true allies, then we recognise that the majority of work should be on supporting those who have *already* experienced trauma. We are so many. 

Code of Conducts do not innoculate us from harm; and explicitly what I feel they fail in is supporting those who are suffering the trauma of experiences with others. Others from within and without. 

But CoCs invite survivors to present themselves in distress. When almost all reaving is unintentional, if the survivor must **prove ill intent** then she is doomed to failure. 

And a much smaller CD collection. 

Worse still, the ubiquity of what Melissa McEwan describes as *Magical Intent* will mean she will relive precisely the type of accountability-deflecting [harmful language](http://www.shakesville.com/2011/12/harmful-communication-part-one-intent.html) she experienced with respect to her trauma. 

The truth that, for the last year, burned up Charles T. Gray's brain is that people genuinely believe it's *enough* to merely proclaim allyship, no matter how they treat me. And that I am not permitted to be hurt because they are Good People. No matter how objectively offensive the behaviour is, and words are, nor how many times it happened. That does not make me feel safe from reaving. But I'm pretty tough, and I've got through things before. What truly concerns me about the arrogance of this ignorance is how the next person experiencing reaving is treated.

I am hurt. I give myself permission and I will not accept I need others'. I will try to [encode my behaviour with kindess](https://softloud.github.io/trophybitch/posts/2019-04-06-coding-of-kindness/). Because kindness should be at the heart of [allyship](http://www.guidetoallyship.com/). 

<blockquote class="twitter-tweet"><p lang="en" dir="ltr">&#39;Imagine your privilege is a heavy boot that keeps you from feeling when you’re stepping on someone’s feet or they’re stepping on yours, while oppressed people have only sandals. “Ouch! You’re stepping on my toes!” How do you react?&#39;<a href="https://t.co/BcGKzXTS0I">https://t.co/BcGKzXTS0I</a> <a href="https://t.co/KROIWgGp1M">pic.twitter.com/KROIWgGp1M</a></p>&mdash; Charles T. Gray (\@cantabile) <a href="https://twitter.com/cantabile/status/1160657825330188288?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw">August 11, 2019</a></blockquote> <script async src="https://platform.twitter.com/widgets.js" charset="utf-8"></script>






## we are all kings, we are all queens

People can surprise you. I surprise people all the time. 

<iframe width="400" height="300" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/AjZNbIQtWvw" frameborder="0" allow="accelerometer; autoplay; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture" allowfullscreen></iframe>


### stop hitting yourself | comfort in, dump out

```{r stophittingyourself,  fig.align='center'}

knitr::include_graphics("../../figs/stophittingyourself.gif")

```

The problem with the cognitive dissonance of denial is that it brings trauma for the instigator.

An important issue to note here, is that however painstakingly patient the attempts to communicate the hurt are, they are received **traumatically** by someone who is in denial.

When an instigator of the initial offense is unable to admit wrongdoing, this prompts a spirited attempt on the offended party why they are hurt. And this is received as an irrational attack, it is received traumatically by the instigator. *I don't need this shit.* 

No matter how hard this is on the instigator, this doesn't mitigate the outcome for the survivor. And that is *really* hard to accept.

You *do* become the victim in the story, because the response is so extreme. *I don't have to take responsibility for what happened to you*. You *should* ask for support and help, **from others**. But you should not ask the survivor to take responsibility for your defensiveness, nor vilify them for making you uncomfortable with what life has made them. 

Give yourself permission for finding it *hard* to empathise. Give yourself permission to be hurt, and seek *others* with whom you can seek comfort. You will need it. Allyship is hard work.


> Here are the basic tenets paraphrased from Silk and Goodman’s article:

>1. Draw a circle. In this circle, write the name of the person at the center of the crisis.
2. Now draw a larger circle around the first one. In this ring, put the name of the person next closest to the crisis.
3. In each larger ring, put the next closest people. As Silk and Goodman state, “Parents and children before more distant relatives. Intimate friends in smaller rings, less intimate friends in larger ones.” [@sandler_ring_2019]


```{r fig.align='center', fig.cap="From Ring Theory, [@sandler_ring_2019]"}

knitr::include_graphics("../../figs/ring_of_grief.jpg")

```


And, for what it's worth, I get it. I feel it. And I *really* empathise. But survivors need **you** to *dump out*, not require us to give far more empathy and kindness than afforded us. 

Allyship is rewarding work. I know I challenge you, and I get it. But asking me to shoulder how hard it is for you, when it is already so hard for me, well, that's something you should share the load with. Because I can't carry this for all of you.

